div.note:
The Latin names of the
						consonants were as follows:—B,
							be (pronounced bay); C, ce (pronounced kay); D, de
							(day); F, ef;
						G, ge (gay);
							H, ha;
						K, ka;
						L, el;
						M, em;
						N, en;
						P, pe (pay);
							Q, qu (koo);
							R, er;
						S, es;
						T, te (tay);
							X, ix;
						Z, zeta (the Greek name,
						pronounced dzayta). The sound of each vowel was
						used as its name.

div.p:
The character C originally meant G, a value always
						retained in the abbreviations C. (for 
							Gāius
						) and Cn. (for 
							Gnaeus
						).

Double consonants are x (= cs) and z (=

								dz
							); h is merely a breathing.

list.item:
Consonant i is like y in
									young;
								v (consonant 
									u
								) like w in wing.

Two vowels coming together are often contracted:—
cōgō for †co-agō;
prōmō for †pro-emō;nīl for nihil; dēbeō for †dē-hibed(† dē-habeō ).

div.note:
Sometimes a consonant
							lost in Latin is still represented in English: as, niv- (for †sniv-), Eng. snow;

								ānser
							 (for †
								hānser
							), Eng. goose.

div.p:
A Noun is the name of a person, place, thing, or idea: as,
						Caesar; Rōma,
							Rome;
						domus, a house;
						virtūs, virtue.

A Pronoun is a word used to distinguish a person, place, thing, or idea
						without either naming or describing it: as, is,
							he;
						quī, who;
						nōs, we.

Inflectional changes sometimes take place in the body of a word, or at the
						beginning, but oftener in its termination:—


								vōx, a voice;
								vōcis, of a voice;
								vocō, I call;
								vocat, he calls;
								vocet, let him call;
								vocāvit, he has
									called;
								tangit, he touches;
								tetigit, he touched.

Natural Gender is distinction as to the sex of the object denoted: as,
							puer (M.), boy;
						puella (F.), girl;
						rēx (M.), king;
						rēgīna (F.), queen.
						Many nouns have both a
							masculine and a feminine form to distinguish sex: as,

								cervus
							, cerva, stag,
								doe;

								cliēns
							, clienta, client;
							victor, victrīx,
								conqueror.

Names of Male beings, and of Rivers, Winds, Months, and Mountains, are
								masculine:—


									pater, father;
									Iūlius, Julius;
									Tiberis, the Tiber;
									auster, south wind;
									Iānuārius,
										January;
									Apennīnus, the
										Apennines.


							Names of Months are
								properly adjectives, the masculine noun mēnsis, month, being
								understood: as, Iānuārius, January.

Names of Female beings, of Cities, Countries, Plants, Trees, and Gems, of
							many Animals (especially Birds), and of most abstract Qualities, are
								feminine:—


									māter, mother;
									Iūlia, Julia;
									Rōma, Rome;
									Ītalia, Italy;
									rosa, rose;
									pīnus, pine;
									sapphīrus,
										sapphire;
									anas, duck;
									vēritās,
										truth.

Indeclinable nouns, infinitives, terms or phrases used as nouns, and
							words quoted merely for their form, are neuter:—


									fās, right;
									nihil, nothing;
									gummī, gum;
									scīre tuum, your
										knowledge (to know); trīste valē, a sad
										farewell;
									hōc ipsum diū,
										this very “long.”

All the cases, except the nominative and vocative, are used as objectcases;
						and are sometimes called Oblique Cases (
							cāsūs
							oblīquī
						).

The Locative form for the singular ends in -ae; for the plural in -īs (cf. p. 34, footnote): as, Rōmae, at Rome;
							Athēnīs, at
								Athens.

Many nouns of the First Declension borrowed from the Greek are entirely
							Latinized (as, aula, court);
							but others retain traces of their Greek case-forms in the singular.

In like manner are declined—
ariēs, -etis (M.), ram; comes, -itis (c.), companion;
lapis , -idis (M.), stone;
iūdex , -icis (M.), judge;
cornīx , -īcis (F.), raven, and many other nouns.

dēns, fōns , mōns , pōns.Some nouns in -is and -ns which are masculine were originally adjectives or participles agreeing with a masculine noun: as, Aprīlis (sc. mēnsis ), M., April;
oriēns (sc. sōl ), M., the east;
annālis (sc. liber ), M., the year-book.

