div.p:
The neuter accusative of adjectives and
								pronouns is often used as an adverb: as, multum, much;
								facil&ebreve;, easily;
								quid, why.

This is the origin of the ending -ius in
								the comparative degree of adverbs (§ 218): as, ācrius, more keenly
								(positive 
									ācriter
								); facilius, more
									easily (positive 
									facil&ebreve;
								).These adverbs are strictly cognate accusatives (§ 390).

The ablative singular neuter or (less
								commonly) feminine of adjectives, pronouns,
								and nouns may be used adverbially: as, falsō, falsely;

									cit&obreve;
								,

quickly (with shortened 
									o
